## 1. Definitions

### 1.1 Licensor

“Licensor” means Guillaume AUSSET and any other copyright holder that validly places material under this License.

### 1.2 Covered Material

“Covered Material” means the software, source code, object code, documentation, comments, examples, tests, build files, configuration files, data files, specifications, diagrams, repository history, patches, and other associated materials accompanied by this License, but only to the extent that a Licensor owns or controls the relevant rights.

Covered Material includes modified, translated, transpiled, compiled, reformatted, minified, obfuscated, annotated, summarized, or otherwise transformed versions of that material to the extent that the Licensor’s protectable expression remains present.

Covered Material does not include separately identified third-party material. Third-party material remains governed by its applicable license.

### 1.3 Excluded Companies

“Excluded Company” means:

1. Anthropic, PBC;
2. OpenAI Foundation;
3. OpenAI Group PBC;
4. OpenAI OpCo, LLC;
5. any entity directly or indirectly controlling, controlled by, or under common control with an entity listed above;
6. any entity into which an entity listed above is merged, converted, reorganized, renamed, or reincorporated;
7. any successor, assignee, purchaser, or transferee carrying on all or a substantial portion of an entity listed above’s artificial-intelligence research, model-development, model-training, model-deployment, or commercial AI business;
8. any entity established to replace, continue, divide, acquire, or operate such a business; and
9. any entity conducting substantially the same business primarily under the “Anthropic,” “Claude,” “OpenAI,” or “ChatGPT” name or brand.

“Control” means:

1. direct or indirect ownership of more than fifty percent of voting power or equity;
2. the direct or indirect power to appoint a majority of an entity’s governing body; or
3. the direct or indirect contractual, legal, or practical power to direct the entity’s management or material policies.

A non-controlling investment, ordinary commercial agreement, cloud-hosting relationship, supplier relationship, or customer relationship does not by itself constitute control.

Microsoft, Amazon, Google, other investors, cloud providers, suppliers, customers, and business partners are not Excluded Companies solely because of a non-controlling investment in, or commercial relationship with, an Excluded Company.

### 1.4 Excluded Personnel

“Excluded Personnel” means any current:

1. director;
2. officer;
3. employee;
4. worker;
5. intern;
6. secondee;
7. temporary worker;
8. individual consultant;
9. individual contractor;
10. agent; or
11. representative

of an Excluded Company.

Excluded Personnel are excluded whether acting professionally, personally, academically, independently, experimentally, non-commercially, anonymously, pseudonymously, or through another person.

A former member of Excluded Personnel is not excluded solely because of that former relationship, unless that person is also a Permanently Excluded Individual or remains otherwise covered by the definition of Excluded Person.

### 1.5 Persons Acting for an Excluded Company

A person or entity is “Acting for an Excluded Company” when that person or entity Knowingly:

1. acts on behalf of an Excluded Company;
2. acts at the request or direction of an Excluded Company;
3. performs work intended for delivery to an Excluded Company;
4. uses the Covered Material for the direct or indirect benefit of an Excluded Company;
5. supplies an Excluded Company with a product, service, dataset, model, benchmark, report, analysis, patch, derivative work, or other deliverable developed using the Covered Material;
6. conducts research or development sponsored by an Excluded Company where that company receives deliverables, privileged access, ownership, licensing rights, preferential access, or another specific benefit arising from the work;
7. obtains, processes, or uses the Covered Material through a contractor, supplier, academic institution, nonprofit organization, customer, partner, agent, proxy, or intermediary for the benefit of an Excluded Company; or
8. serves as an intermediary intended to avoid or circumvent this License.

General funding, an unrestricted donation, ordinary use of an Excluded Company’s publicly available products or APIs, or provision of generally available goods or services does not by itself mean that a person is Acting for an Excluded Company.

### 1.6 Permanently Excluded Individuals

“Permanently Excluded Individual” means each natural person identified in Schedule A.

The exclusion attaches to the identity of the natural person and not merely to the spelling or presentation of that person’s name.

A Permanently Excluded Individual remains excluded notwithstanding:

1. a legal or informal name change;
2. use of an alias, pseudonym, nickname, professional name, married name, transliteration, abbreviation, initials, or other identifier;
3. a change of employer, office, occupation, affiliation, citizenship, nationality, domicile, residence, or legal capacity;
4. resignation, dismissal, retirement, termination, suspension, leave, divestment, or cessation of any relationship with an Excluded Company;
5. acting personally, professionally, academically, politically, philanthropically, commercially, independently, anonymously, pseudonymously, or through another person;
6. acting as an employee, director, officer, investor, founder, adviser, consultant, contractor, trustee, partner, agent, representative, beneficiary, or fiduciary;
7. use of a personal, family, academic, governmental, nonprofit, corporate, contractor, customer, partner, or third-party account;
8. acquisition of the Covered Material before or after becoming associated with an Excluded Company; or
9. any merger, restructuring, dissolution, renaming, sale, or reorganization affecting an Excluded Company.

Descriptions in Schedule A are included solely to identify the intended natural person. They are not conditions of exclusion.

No other person is excluded solely because that person has the same or a similar name.

### 1.7 Personal Controlled Vehicle

“Personal Controlled Vehicle” means a corporation, partnership, trust, foundation, fund, association, limited-liability entity, unincorporated organization, family office, investment vehicle, or other legal arrangement that a Permanently Excluded Individual directly or indirectly controls.

For this purpose, “controls” means possessing the practical or legal power to direct the management or material activities of the vehicle, whether through ownership, voting rights, appointment rights, agreement, trusteeship, beneficial ownership, or otherwise.

A company, university, government body, nonprofit organization, or other employer is not an Excluded Person solely because it employs or engages a Permanently Excluded Individual.

However, no such organization receives authority to permit that Permanently Excluded Individual personally to access, use, direct, supervise, commission, benefit from, or participate in activity involving the Covered Material.

### 1.8 Excluded Persons

“Excluded Person” means:

1. every Excluded Company;
2. every member of Excluded Personnel;
3. every Permanently Excluded Individual;
4. every Personal Controlled Vehicle;
5. every person or entity Acting for an Excluded Company in connection with the Covered Material;
6. every person or entity Knowingly acting for, at the direction of, on behalf of, or for the specific benefit of a Permanently Excluded Individual in connection with the Covered Material; and
7. every nominee, proxy, intermediary, agent, trustee, fiduciary, contractor, supplier, or other person Knowingly used to avoid or circumvent an exclusion imposed by this License.

### 1.9 Eligible Person

“Eligible Person” means every natural person and legal entity that is not an Excluded Person.

### 1.10 Derived Training Material

“Derived Training Material” means any material created from, containing, representing, describing, transforming, or encoding Covered Material, including:

1. excerpts and fragments;
2. patches and diffs;
3. translations and transpiled versions;
4. abstract syntax trees;
5. intermediate representations;
6. token sequences;
7. embeddings and feature vectors;
8. summaries and descriptions;
9. annotations and labels;
10. question-and-answer pairs;
11. prompts and completions;
12. execution traces;
13. test cases;
14. synthetic examples;
15. rewritten or obfuscated variants;
16. generated documentation;
17. code-review data;
18. preference data;
19. reward data;
20. evaluation results;
21. benchmark results; and
22. any dataset entry materially derived from Covered Material.

### 1.11 Machine-Learning Activity

“Machine-Learning Activity” means any use or processing of Covered Material or Derived Training Material:

1. to train, pretrain, continue training, fine-tune, align, adapt, optimize, or otherwise develop a model;
2. for supervised, unsupervised, self-supervised, semi-supervised, contrastive, reinforcement, preference-based, or imitation learning;
3. to train a reward model, preference model, critic, verifier, classifier, router, retriever, embedding model, reranker, or agent;
4. for model distillation, extraction, imitation, cloning, compression, quantization-aware training, or knowledge transfer;
5. to generate synthetic data used in model development;
6. to evaluate, validate, benchmark, grade, compare, select, reject, modify, align, release, or deploy a model;
7. to develop or improve code generation, code completion, code review, code search, vulnerability analysis, automated reasoning, or software-development capabilities;
8. as part of a retrieval-augmented generation system;
9. as part of a search index, vector database, retrieval corpus, context store, knowledge base, model memory, or model-accessible repository;
10. to generate embeddings, representations, labels, rewards, rankings, preferences, critiques, summaries, or feedback;
11. to test memorization, contamination, provenance, safety, capability, reliability, security, or model behavior;
12. in prompts, system prompts, tool contexts, agent memory, model context, or evaluation contexts;
13. through crawling, scraping, harvesting, cloning, downloading, indexing, parsing, tokenizing, normalizing, deduplicating, embedding, feature extraction, or data selection; or
14. at any other stage of an artificial-intelligence or machine-learning data, training, evaluation, alignment, inference, retrieval, deployment, or improvement pipeline.

Machine-Learning Activity includes activity performed manually, automatically, directly, indirectly, internally, externally, or through any contractor, data provider, cloud provider, model provider, agent, service, proxy, or intermediary.

### 1.12 Knowingly

“Knowingly” means with actual knowledge.

A person acquires actual knowledge when the Licensor provides that person with written notice identifying the relevant relationship or prohibited activity.

An Eligible Person is not required to investigate, monitor, identify, screen, audit, or verify customers, users, investors, suppliers, employees, contractors, or counterparties merely to determine whether an unknown relationship exists.

